<TEXT>
the japanese have gone wild over fourwheel 
drive vehicles and on that score they have shed their prejudices 
against american automobiles 
the americanmade jeep is the mark of prestige 
churning up mud bouncing over dirt moguls mucking through boggy 
sinkholes enthusiasts careen around a 55acre fourwheeldrive 
playground in the shadow of mount fuji 
the equivalent of a ski resort for dirt vehicles the 
paybytheday motosu highlands course is flourishing because herds 
of fourwheeldrive vehicles were banned from tearing up mount fuji 
itself 
but the fourwheeldrive vehicle also has become a status symbol 
in tokyos highfashion harajuku district where urban dandies 
cruise around in chrometrimmed jackedup jeeptype vehicles with 
the tops down festooned with macho but unused heavyduty winches 
and fog lights 
and in affluent residential neighborhoods housewives load 
groceries into jeep cherokees parked next to mercedes benzes and 
saabs 
in a country eager for evermorestylish ways to spend newfound 
cash fourwheeldrive recreational vehicles have become the 
ultimate japanese yuppie vehicle and the american jeep is the one 
to own 
while other american cars are deemed mediocre by the japanese 
jeeps evoke an image of american wideopen spaces and outdoor life 
that many japanese long for says nobuyoshi fukushima editor of 4x4 
magazine 
chrysler jeep sales have doubled in japan for three years in a 
row but they still totaled only 500 in 1988 
the vast majority of fourwheeldrive cars on japanese roads are 
still domestic models such as the mitsubishi pajero or isuzu big 
horn and many vehicles with the genuine jeep insignia were built by 
mitsubishi which bought the technology from the willis overland co 
more than 20 years ago before jeep manufacturing was taken over in 
the united states by american motors corp and then chrysler 
fourwheeldrive vehicles are the fastestgrowing segment of 
japans auto market for the past few years jeeptype sales have 
grown 20 to 30 percent annually or three times as fast as the 
entire car market estimates fukushima one in 11 of the 67 million 
cars produced in japan last year had fourwheel drive 
recreation vehicles are part of a growing leisure industry fueled 
by rising incomes and longer vacations skiers surfers and scuba 
divers also are avid drivers of jeepstyle vehicles but 75 percent 
of fourwheeldrives in japan never leave city streets their appeal 
is atmospheric rather than functional 
jeepstyle vehicles with power steering leather seats stereos 
adjustable suspensions and automatic transmissions sell fast and 
dealers say theyre getting bmw tradeins from buyers 
the topoftheline us jeep cherokee costs about 35000 in 
japan more than double the price of many smaller japanese 
jeepstyle cars 
this is really a luxury car for welltodo buyers mostly 
professionals in their late 30s or 40s says masayuki sakamoto 
director of marketing for chrysler japan sales ltd 
masaaki kuroiwa who has been selling jeeps and jeep parts for 
more than 20 years from a cluttered suburban garage finds the fad a 
little ironic 
theres no need for these cars in japan nowadays he said 
theres hardly any place to really drive them its just a 
fashion people like them with all kinds of shiny accessories stuck 
on its a way to spend money 
kuroiwa fell in love with jeeps when they were the only vehicles 
that could get around in a devastated japan just after world war ii 
as a child he admired the powerful olivegreen vehicles driven by 
american occupation troops 
after the us occupation forces left japan their jeeps 
continued to serve as allround vehicles especially on rough 
country roads but they nearly disappeared in the 1960s when many 
were shipped to poorer countries for another lifetime of service 
now kuroiwa and others are buying vintage american jeeps as 
collectors items from the philippines where they are still widely 
in use 
in kuroiwas lot yuichi tanaka 45 proudly pats the hood of his 
wellpreserved jeep which is exactly as old as he is 
its won a lot of jeep beauty contests he said 
</TEXT>
