<TEXT>
the farm crisis hot line is disconnected 
but officials say farmers and university of illinois advisers who 
help them are wiser because of rural route 
the unique program ended this summer after 3500 farmers called 
its tollfree number seeking confidential advice about their 
financial problems 
rural route which received 22 million in state and federal 
funds over four years has left both farmers and advisers better 
prepared for the future said peter bloome assistant director of 
the university cooperative extension service 
they have a vivid memory of a recent event that will make them 
more cautious he said farmers also have learned that farming is 
a business and that they have a value and worth that has nothing 
to do with that occupation 
rural route also taught university advisers to be aggressive in 
looking for solutions to farmers economic problems and preparing 
farmers for their future in agriculture or in some other occupation 
if necessary said bloome 
some wanted to pretend the men in trouble were older poorly 
educated smaller farmers who were laggards at accepting 
technology he said the opposite was true they were young 
welleducated and progressive 
the hot line was unplugged july 1 although the services remain 
available 
calls had dropped to one a day or less said bloome the 
overall financial picture for farmers was much improved and 
farmers need for anonymity seemed to be less 
when the first call came into rural route on march 18 1985 
farm income was down debt and operating costs were up and many 
farmers felt a serious economic pinch 
bills and stress mounted foreclosure loomed for some there 
was an increase in alcohol abuse family discord divorce and 
suicide but many troubled farmers refused to seek help because of 
pride and fear of ridicule in their communities 
farmers were referred to counseling centers around the state or 
advisers always from another county were dispatched to their 
farms 
