<TEXT>
this communist land of comparative 
plenty long a magnet for soviet bloc citizens seeking consumer 
goods and comfortable vacations also is becoming an escape route to 
the west 
on sunday night a dozen young east germans who spent the weekend 
outside the west german consulate in hopes of reaching the west 
crawled into their sleeping bags for another night on the sidewalk 
police drove by now and then but did not disturb them 
across the danube river a new interior ministry committee was 
examining requests for refugee status from 10 applicants a soviet 
citizen a czechoslovak and eight stranded somalis 
three refugee camps for 1400 people are being built outside 
budapest they are primarily intended for ethnic hungarians from 
romania but officials say the camps will be open to all europeans 
who can prove they face persecution at home 
one of the young east germans said we still dont know whether 
well make it but the way west is a lot easier from hungary than 
from east berlin 
hungary began welcoming romanian refugees in january 1988 
breaking an agreement with the communist ally to return its citizens 
who sought asylum 
about 17000 romanians most of them ethnic hungarians have fled 
to hungary in the first instance of one warsaw pact country giving 
sanctuary to citizens of another on grounds of persecution 
hungarys decision to take in refugees from romania put a further 
burden on the already strained relations between the two allies 
hungary has long maintained the estimated 17 millionmember 
ethnic hungarian minority in romania is subject to discriminatory 
policies hungary also has expressed concern over a romanian plan to 
demolish villages and resettle the population hungary fears that 
this could destroy ethnic culture and traditions 
romania rejects the charges as interference in its internal 
affairs 
hungarian officials said in recent interviews the country will 
not change its new border and refugee policies just to avoid 
tensions with allies 
in may hungary began dismantling barbed wire and other barriers 
on its border with austria since then at least 1500 east germans 
with few chances of travel to western europe have tried to cross 
into austria illegally through hungary 
hundreds succeeded and have gone on to west germany other 
hundreds who failed have gone underground in hungary or sought 
asylum on west german diplomatic property 
police col karoly nagy urged all people who are in hungary 
illegally to leave but also told reporters none would be forcibly 
deported 
a government official said privately because this decision 
expands the possibility for the east germans to go to the west 
illegally its clear that this decision is not among those that the 
east germans are happy about 
the new refugee policy which could provide asylum to any east 
european who proved persecution is likely to disturb hungarys east 
european allies even more 
on march 14 hungary became the first soviet bloc country to join 
the un convention on the rights of refugees which took effect 
june 12 
it commits authorities not to return anyone to a country where 
his life or freedom would be threatened on account of his race 
religion nationality or political opinion 
some western countries have applied the convention broadly 
giving asylum to most citizens of soviet bloc countries 
the interior ministry insists hungary does not want to become a 
conduit to the west but officials formulating new laws to conform 
with the convention say all cases will be heard 
if an individual meets the criteria of the geneva convention 
then we will definitely grant him refugee status because if we 
decided to accept something we have to carry it through said 
laszlo albrecht deputy head of the ministrys refugee section 
i cannot speak for the czechoslovak or east german governments 
but in case they disapprove what can we do 
under new laws taking effect in october each applicant will be 
heard by a refugee camp panel albrecht said a refugee who is 
rejected may appeal to an interior ministry committee then demand a 
court hearing 
albrecht said other countries of permanent residence would be 
sought for most refugees other than ethnic hungarians indicating 
most would come from the east and go west 
its clear that not too many swiss citizens are going to ask 
for refugee status from us he said and smiled 
