<TEXT>
outrage over drugrelated crime has spawned 
calls for more police and prisons but a school for judges hopes to 
teach jurists to wage war on drugs with treatment rather than tough 
jail terms 
the national judicial college is launching an instructional 
program to show judges how to handle criminals who have drug 
problems 
theres an onslaught of drugrelated cases coming into the 
courts right now across the country said thomas russell 
assistant dean of the renobased institution 
what were trying to do is teach judges patterns of drug use 
and about evaluation and treatment programs so they dont just order 
criminals to be locked up every time 
one judge in each state has been invited to enroll in the 
inaugural oneweek program which begins sunday russell said at 
least 44 judges selected by each states chief judge plan to attend 
the course will become a regular offering next march at the 
judicial college whose alumni range from local judges to supreme 
court justice sandra day oconnor 
the school offers short courses mostly lasting one to four 
weeks they range from basic instruction for new appointees to the 
bench to retraining for experienced jurists the private school 
located on the university of nevadas reno campus is funded by 
state and federal grants as well as tuition 
chicago circuit court judge michael getty one of the main 
instructors for next weeks course said he aims to teach jurists to 
recognize when it would be better to sentence a criminal to 
treatment instead of prison time 
neither the penitentiary nor probation by themselves are an 
adequate response to this countrys drug crimes problems getty 
said 
in chicago for example getty said judges sometimes sentence 
nonviolent criminals who have drug problems to residential or 
nonresidential treatment programs along with community service 
the recidivism rate for treatment programs is not as high as if 
you send them to prison he said from that point of view these 
types of programs are a tremendous success 
that message appears to stand in contrast to increasingly 
strident calls for tougher law enforcement 
last week us attorney general dick thornburgh outlined the 
bush administrations 1 billion crimefighting package including 
harsher penalties for the criminal use of guns ending plea 
bargaining in such cases hiring more investigators and prosecutors 
and doubling space in federal prisons 
getty said drugusing criminals who commit violent crimes must 
pay through incarceration 
im not advocating that all drug offenders not go to prison 
he said but there are a significant number who ought to be placed 
in treatment programs rather than prisons 
according to the national conference of state legislatures 62 
percent of the 605000 people in state and federal prisons in 1988 
used drugs regularly before they were incarcerated 
of those 27 percent used drugs daily according to donna 
hunzeker criminal justice program manager for the national 
lawmakers group twentytwo percent were under the influence of 
drugs while committing the crime for which they were sentenced to 
prison she added 
the studies show that drug use accelerates criminal behavior 
ms hunzeker said 
russell the assistant dean said he hopes that by treating 
people for drug problems crime can be reduced 
part of the solution to reducing the high crime rate is to find 
the problems and deal directly with them russell said the role 
of the judge will be to recognize when the problem is drugs 
</TEXT>
