<TEXT>
key dates in the life of pw 
botha 
jan 12 1916 born on farm in the orange free state 
may 1 1936 quits university to take job as an organizer for 
the national party in the cape province 
19391940 helps form cape province branch of the ossewabrandwag 
oxwagon fire guard a group sympathetic to the nazis and opposed 
south africa joining the allied side in world war ii threatened 
with internment but turns against the ossewabrandwag when it split 
with national party leaders 
march 13 1943 marries elize rossouw 
may 26 1948 becomes a member of parliament from george in 
cape province as his national party comes to power 
october 1958 is appointed deputy minister of the interior 
duties include close involvement with administering the group areas 
act which segregates residential and business areas by race 
aug 2 1961 becomes a cabinet minister in charge of community 
development and colored mixedrace affairs 
april 5 1966 becomes minister of defense and is instrumental 
in making south africa nearly selfsufficient in arms despite a 
united nations arms embargo 
1966 is elected leader of the national party in cape province 
one of four powerful provincial leadership posts from which party 
leaders are chosen 
sept 28 1978 becomes national party leader and prime 
minister following resignation of bj vorster 
1979 becomes first national leader to visit a black township 
soweto 
1982 national party rightwing breaks away forming 
conservative party in response to bothas plans to include indians 
and people of mixedrace in parliament in separate chambers meets 
with zambian president kenneth kaunda 
1984 new constitution is adopted creating the threechambered 
parliament that excludes the black majority and changes bothas 
title from prime minister to president with wideranging powers 
tours europe and declares apartheid is dead 
june 12 1986 declares national emergency to subdue unrest and 
nationwide violence that erupted in black communities in response to 
the new constitution 
jan 18 1989 suffers a stroke and subsequently gives up 
leadership of national party 
march 1989 under pressure from party leaders agrees to resign 
from presidency following sept 6 parliamentary elections 
july 5 1989 invites imprisoned african national congress 
leader nelson mandela to his official cape town residence for 
conversation 
aug 14 1989 announces his resignation 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

