<TEXT>
with the collapse of complete communist 
control of parliament the once docile united peasants party has 
emerged as an independent political force whose leaders seem 
determined to play a major role 
prime minister gen czeslaw kiszczak said monday he is ready to 
give up trying to form a government in favor of roman malinowski 
the leader of the peasant party 
malinowski who has favored continuing his partys historical 
alliance with the communist party would be asked to create a 
cabinet composed of representatives of all forces in parliament 
according to kiszczak 
but the 54yearold economist who has led the party since 1981 
and was among top communist coalition candidates who were defeated 
in june parliamentary elections faces opposition from peasant 
lawmakers in parliament who fear reprisals at the polls if the 
partys links with the unpopular communists are not cut 
led by aleksander bentkowski their independentminded 
parliamentary floor leader at least one third of the 76 peasant 
deputies favor forming a coalition government with solidarity 
as the thirdlargest group in parliament in which neither the 
larger communists or solidarity lawmakers holds a majority the 
peasants suddenly have been catapulted into the role of kingmaker 
the split between the party leadership and its representatives in 
parliament comes as the peasants search for a new identity in 
response to voter disenchantment with the old party model and with 
an eye to completely free elections promised in the future 
the peasant movement in poland has deep roots with the first 
organized polish peasant party founded in rzeszow then in 
austriaruled galicia in 1895 rzeszow now in southeast poland 
remains a center of rural activism 
before and after world war ii the party advocated land reform to 
free the peasantry from the control of large wealthy landowners in 
prewar poland it was an important political force with its leader 
wincenty witos serving as premier three times 
one of its leaders stanislaw mikolajczyk also headed the polish 
governmentinexile in london during world war ii 
the polish peasants party enjoyed a brief period of independent 
activity in poland after world war ii but the communist party that 
swept to power as a result of soviet military might forced the 
merger of the independent party known as the psl with a 
procommunist peasant party the sl in 1949 to form the zsl as 
the united peasant party is now known 
in that era of stalinist purges independent peasant leaders were 
forced to flee the country step down or bend to communist rule 
in the most notorious case mikolajczyk the wartime premier and 
only member of the london government to risk coming back to poland 
after the war to join a communistled coalition fled in 1947 when 
it became clear he was facing arrest and a show trial 
he was denounced as a spy and lost his citizenship in 1949 only 
this year was his citizenship restored posthumously by the council 
of state 
for most of the history of the polish peoples republic the 
peasant party like the other minor party the democrats has 
obediently followed communist policy 
in the last decade as a result of political reforms the peasant 
party has been allowed to develop a more independent policy while 
still acknowledging the communist partys leading role it 
traditionally has exercised broad powers in rural areas and often 
holds the ministry of agriculture 
the zsl claims a membership of 500000 and says it represents the 
interests of farmers 
peasant deputies resenting communist domination of the policies 
of their own party were critical of malinowskis defense of 
continued obedience to the communists at a caucus last week 
deputies favoring a coalition with solidarity also have said 
their constituents resented kiszczaks election as prime minister 
because it left the impression that nothing has changed despite 
solidaritys victory at the polls in june 
the internal revolt within the zsl took on a new dimension 
tuesday as 120 peasant activists from around the country met in 
warsaw and decided to resume the activities of mikolajczyks old 
psl which was declared illegal in 1947 the state news agency pap 
said 
participants who included representatives from rural solidarity 
the independent farmers union said the party would be revived on 
the basis of the program adopted by the psl in 1946 
