in washington the state department said it hoped for an active 
dialogue with the new leadership on ending apartheid the official 
policy of racial discrimination it held out the possibility of a 
visit by de klerk who also heads the governing national party 
botha who led south africa for 11 often turbulent years 
resigned monday night after repeated confrontations with his cabinet 
national party leaders tried to persuade the 73yearold 
president to leave gracefully after he suffered a stroke jan 18 
but botha refused his stubborn defiant manner resulted in 
embarrassing public battles likely to hurt the party in 
parliamentary elections sept 6 
there was no evidence of policy disputes with the cabinet but 
younger leaders appeared to believe bothas age health and growing 
political isolation made him unable to continue the gradual limited 
reforms he introduced in the early 1980s 
after nationwide black unrest developed in 1984 botha 
increasingly turned away from reform and relied on repression to 
stifle black political demands 
de klerk praised botha on tuesday for starting reform 
his greatest gift to south africa is the fact that he has put 
our country on the road to fundamental reform that he has 
successfully started pulling south africa out of its deadend 
streets he told reporters after being sworn in by chief justice 
michael corbett 
he repeated his intention to speed reform but did not pledge 
specific action on such major apartheid issues as sharing power with 
blacks who outnumber whites 28 million to 5 million and have no 
voice in national affairs 
we want to build a new south africa in which all people 
participate in decisions affecting their lives at all levels de 
klerk said 
i trust that the people of south africa will show the courage 
and vision required to break the cycle of conflict tension and 
isolation that has gripped us for so long 
since taking over from botha in february as leader of the 
national party which has governed since 1948 de klerk has stressed 
the need for immediate reform to end south africas deep racial 
divisions and international isolation 
his speeches are more conciliatory than bothas his personal 
style affable rather than confrontational at age 53 he belongs to 
a younger generation more receptive to change 
through 17 years in politics however he has been a loyal 
supporter of the national party including limited race reforms 
that reject majority rule de klerk has not set himself apart from 
any botha policies and has yet to name apartheid laws he would 
repeal 
the african national congress the main guerrilla movement 
fighting white supremacy said botha dedicated his life to the 
