<TEXT>
the agriculture department has awarded a total 
of 200 million to 46 organizations under the targeted export 
assistance program for the fiscal year that will begin on oct 1 
the department announced tuesday 
under tea as the program is called trade associations get funds 
to carry out overseas promotion of designated agricultural products 
the program is aimed at countering or offsetting adverse effects of 
unfair foreign trade practices on us exports 
in most cases the sponsoring organizations put up some of their 
own money in carrying out specific projects the amount of those 
contributions vary and are subject to negotiation with the 
departments foreign agricultural service the agency that oversees 
the program 
the 200 million allocated by usda is the same as for the current 
fiscal year a level set by congress in 1989 appropriations 
legislation 
officials said the 1990 allocations will be finalized after 
congress completes work on next years appropriations bill 
the largest amount for next fiscal year was 154 million 
reserved for cotton council international to promote raw cotton in 
overseas markets followed by 125 million for the california 
raisin advisory board 
other leading recipients included american soybean association 
115 million florida department of citrus 99 million and the 
