<TEXT>
a wasp no bigger than the dot of an i 
could play a big role in the fight against lyme disease following 
its rediscovery by a victim of the ailment who was searching through 
old newspaper files 
the state on tuesday awarded a 15000 grant to the university of 
massachusetts at amherst to collect chalcid wasps reproduce them 
and eventually let them loose on the deer tick that carries lyme 
disease 
theres very exciting possibilities there for some control of 
the problem that has really panicked some people who summer here 
said william wilcox senior county agriculture agent for marthas 
vineyard and nantucket 
we need more information but it looks like theres potential 
there said roy van driesche an entomology professor involved in 
the project 
the minuscule wasp took on new prominence after a member of the 
marthas vineyard lyme disease action committee started to poke 
around in the vineyard gazette files wilcox said 
burton engley a 76yearold marthas vineyard resident who had 
suffered two mild cases of lyme disease said he was trying to track 
down reports of an experiment he recalled from the 1920s 
he found a 1937 article that reported a 1926 experiment in which 
chalcid wasps from europe were released on the island to kill dog 
and wood ticks that fit with a 1985 study that found the wasps 
eggs had infested and were killing nearly 27 percent of the deer 
ticks on the island 
its just a lucky break actually that it worked out that way 
wilcox said 
local health officials then contacted the university of 
massachusetts applied biological control program to explore the 
possibility of using the chalcid wasps for disease control 
lyme disease named for the connecticut town where it was first 
documented in 1975 can cause rashes headaches and sore muscles 
and if not detected early arthritis and heart irregularities it 
can be treated with antibiotics 
between 5000 and 8000 cases of lyme disease are reported 
nationally each year and 350 cases have been documented in 
massachusetts since officials began documenting the disease in 1985 
said paul etkind state epidemiologist 
if this works it could maybe reduce incidents by 35 percent 
said august schumacher jr commissioner of food and agriculture 
thats 100 cases 
the chalcid kills ticks by using a needlelike appendage to 
insert eggs inside the host as the eggs develop they kill the 
tick the wasp also may help inhibit immature ticks from spreading 
the disease health officials said 
researchers hope to begin work soon at a field station on 
nantucket van driesche said 
if the wasps prove effective state officials hope to have them 
commercially bred and used in conjunction with the current burning 
techniques and pesticides 
it could be part of spring in massachusetts would be releasing 
a box of these bugs schumacher said 
</TEXT>
