territory also known as southwest africa heads toward 
independence 
pienaar said the relative calm in namibia allowed the policemen 
to be confined to bases where they will undergo reorientation and 
retraining to equip them for roles that are to be redefined 
if the situation should in any way deteriorate i shall 
consider the steps that would need to be taken in order to restore 
law and order he added 
united nations officials including secretarygeneral javier 
perez de cuellar had said that former koevoet members were 
intimidating civilians in northern namibia and should be removed 
from the 6000member namibian police force 
un military and civilian personnel are in namibia to monitor 
the transition to independence the territory has been administered 
by south africa since world war i under a mandate from the defunct 
league of nations 
koevoet squads played a leading role in the south africanled 
security forces battle against guerrillas of the southwest africa 
peoples organization swao 
most koevoet members were black namibians some civilians accused 
the unit of brutality and atrocities it was disbanded in january 
many exkoevoet members have been integrated into the regular 
police force pienaar had argued the exkoevoet fighters were needed 
