president bush on tuesday promised a 
balanced decisive effective and achievable national drug plan 
backed by more federal money to meet americans demand for action 
he declined to say where the money would come from because the 
final decisions havent been made 
bush said he would not raise taxes but we are going to expand 
federal expenditures he added we will have to do some 
reallocation of resources 
bush focused on the antidrug campaign on his last day at the 
white house before leaving for a threeweek vacation in 
kennebunkport maine 
he told reporters at a news conference that his drug policy 
coordinator william bennett has given him an outline of the 
developing national drug strategy 
its balanced decisive effective and achievable and it will 
target all aspects of the problem it will call for commitment and 
sacrifice and understanding but its clear to me that the american 
people demand no less he said 
he said final details of the plan will be worked out over the 
next several weeks before he announces the specifics on sept 5 
bennetts proposal would target drug users as well as strengthen 
enforcement a draft of the plan obtained by the associated press 
calls for users to be arrested and fined and to lose their drivers 
licenses their cars their federal grants if they have any 
bush discussed whether to put federal financial muscle behind 
such proposals in a meeting tuesday with his domestic policy council 
of advisers 
as drafted the plan would withhold federal highway funds from 
states that did not revoke drug offenders licenses and it would 
withhold federal criminal justice funds from states that dont 
perform drug tests on people in the criminal justice system schools 
receiving federal money would have to have firm prevention programs 
white house spokeswoman alixe glen said bush was still weighing 
those ideas 
during his presidential campaign bush supported revocation of 
drug offenders drivers licenses 
the draft strategy would seek a 49 percent increase in federal 
treatment money for 1990 to 925 million 12 billion for new 
prison construction a 200 million increase for state and local law 
enforcement and 50 million for the department of housing and urban 
development most of it for security improvements at public housing 
projects 
the president asked tuesday if he planned to cut other programs 
to fund the antidrug war said he could not state where the money 
would come from because the final decisions havent been made 
but we will have to do some reallocation of resources theres no 
question about that 
pressed on how he would come up with the funds he added were 
in a period of hard times in the sense that we dont have all the 
money that we would like to spend in several areas 
at the same time he expressed determination to reduce the federal 
budget deficit and stay within the spending limits set by 
congressional budget writers 
