<TEXT>
the federal reserve isnt likely to lower 
interest rates any time soon to boost economic growth despite a 
pointed warning of recession from president bushs budget director 
many economists say 
analysts predicted monday that interest rates will hold steady 
because the central bank is satisfied it has done all it needs to 
keep the country out of an economic slump 
those economists suggested that comments by budget director 
richard darman might actually backfire and make the central bank 
less inclined to ease credit conditions for fear of appearing to bow 
to political pressure 
darman complained that the central bank was keeping interest 
rates too high and would shoulder the blame if the country falls 
into a recession 
if we do have a recession i think it will be because they 
erred on the side of caution in fighting inflation by keeping 
interest rates too high darman said sunday on nbcs meet the 
press 
the white house tried to soften the sting from darmans message 
by praising the fed on monday for generally doing a good job but 
bush today generally endorsed the comments during a morning press 
conference 
bush praised darman for expressing his views which he called 
very balanced 
i feel very comfortable with his darmans sallying forth 
bush said i think i have said the same things in the past 
bush said he did not know of any president who had ever come out 
against lower interest rates but he stopped short of saying that he 
believed that if a recession did occur it would be the fault of the 
central bank 
private economists were surprised by the timing of darmans 
criticism given recent economic statistics such as a drop in the 
jobless rate in august that suggest the economy isnt as sluggish as 
previously feared 
there is virtually no chance that we will have a recession this 
year so why stir up this fuss and get financial markets unsettled 
when you dont have to asked michael evans head of a washington 
forecasting company 
but other economists said they believed darman was positioning 
the fed to take the blame if the economy does weaken and the country 
ends up in a recession right before next years congressional 
elections 
this is a classic situation of setting up the fed to be the 
fall guy if something goes wrong said robert dederick chief 
economist at northern trust co of chicago 
dederick and other economists said it was unlikely that darmans 
remarks would have any impact on upcoming fed decisions top fed 
policymakers will meet again in washington on aug 22 
many economists said they expected the central bank to hold 
interest rates steady and not ease further given recent signs that 
certain key sectors such as consumer spending are rebounding 
so long as the economy is ok there is no reason for the fed to 
ease any more said allen sinai chief economist of the boston co 
from march 1988 through march 1989 the federal reserve pushed 
shortterm interest rates higher in an antiinflation campaign the 
fed reversed course in june and has made three modest moves to lower 
interest rates by making more money available to the banking system 
banks have been able to cut their prime lending rate since early 
june by a full percentage point to 105 percent home mortgage rates 
have declined as well dropping below 10 percent to stand at 996 
percent for fixedrate loans 
sinai said he believed mortgage rates have hit their low for the 
year and may even climb by about onefourth percentage point in 
coming weeks as financial markets realize that the central bank has 
decided to hold off on further easing moves 
paul getman senior economist at the wefa group a bala cynwyd 
pa consulting company said the fed was correct to pause before 
driving interest rates any lower 
he said if economic activity turns out to be stronger in the 
second half of the year than forecast the fed would run the risk of 
triggering higher inflation next year by loosening credit conditions 
too rapidly 
