<TEXT>
chrysler corp tentatively plans to boost prices 
of its 1990 model cars by an average 5 percent the automaker said 
tuesday and blames much of the rise on the cost of 
federallymandated passenger restraints such as air bags 
price hikes outlined by the nations thirdlargest automaker 
would boost the price of a chrysler lebaron coupe by 87 percent to 
12495 and of a subcompact plymouth horizon by 607 percent to 
6995 for example 
the federal government is requiring that all cars made in the 
united states after sept 1 have driverside air bags or automatic 
seat belts as standard equipment 
chrysler and ford motor co said they will install air bags on 
about 1 million cars each during the 1990 model year and general 
motors corp said it will have the devices on about half as many 
earlier this week gm announced a tentative 34 percent increase 
in its 1990 car prices nearly 1 percent of it blamed on air bags 
ford division general manager thomas wagner said earlier this month 
that his company will boost car prices about 48 percent 
chrysler spokeswoman karen stewart said tuesday that air bags 
will add about 450 to the price of each usmade chrysler car 
although thats less than the automaker actually is spending on 
buying and installing the devices she declined to say exactly how 
much the company is spending on air bags 
the rest of chryslers price increase stems from economic 
reasons including higher material and labor costs she said 
those figures are a bit lower than some analysts expected and may 
not include much padding for buyer incentives that can be factored 
into any carbuying deal 
there has been speculation that the big three are eager to get 
out of the incentive war they have been in since early april 
