<TEXT>
the government has announced new rules 
allowing foreign investment in the nationalized petroleum industry 
hoping to attract 8 billion over the next five years and modernize 
the industry 
this is the first time we have defined clearly what foreign 
investment is allowed in petrochemical products alfredo elias 
spokesman for the mexican petrochemical commission said at a news 
conference tuesday 
the commission has ruled that 15 oilbased products are now open 
to 40 percent private investment by foreign and domestic interests 
elias said those products were formerly reserved exclusively for 
the national oil company petroleos de mexico also known as pemex 
the new rules also allow about 350 tertiary petrochemical 
products to be manufactured with 100 percent private investment 
these include about 100 plastics products 
loosening pemexs grip on petroleum byproducts follows a may 
announcement that the government was allowing greater foreign 
ownership in mexican companies 
president carlos salinas gortaris administration has been 
striving to increase foreign investment and make the notoriously 
ineffectual oil industry more efficient and less corrupt 
its important for mexico to be integrated in world commerce 
and that we modernize technology elias said 
the mexican constitution reserves primary petrochemical product 
manufacture to the government only secondary and tertiary products 
come under the new ruling 
the energy mines and parastate companies department projects 
pemex investments of 15 billion through 1995 the government 
expects to attract an additional 8 billion from foreign and 
domestic private investors elias said 
foreign companies that have shown an interest in investing 
include du pont union carbide corp hoechst celanese corp and 
shell oil co he added 
the government hopes to increase petrochemical exports and 
decrease imports under the new scheme he said 
investment of 40 percent will be allowed in producing vinyl 
acetate acetone acrylic acid anhydrous acid chlorobenzenes 
ammonium phosphate isoprene isopropanal ammonium nitrate 
ammonium sulfate polypropylenes and urea these are all secondary 
products 
pemex will maintain exclusive control over 20 primary 
petrochemical products derived from the first refinement of crude 
oil they include benzene ethanol methanol propylene nparaffins 
and toluene 
